  "prompt": "What is creamy layer?",
  "response": "The term \"creamy layer\" is primarily used in the context of reservation policies in India, particularly regarding the allocation of benefits to certain groups based on caste and socioeconomic status. The creamy layer refers to the relatively affluent and well-educated members within the Other Backward Classes (OBCs) community who are considered to have absorbed the benefits of affirmative action and are, therefore, ineligible for certain government benefits and reservations in educational institutions and public employment.\n\nThe concept aims to ensure that the benefits intended for the backward classes reach those who are genuinely disadvantaged and not those who have already improved their social and economic status. The criteria to determine the creamy layer can include income limits, employment status, and educational qualifications, although specific benchmarks can vary and may be updated periodically based on government policies.\n\nThis classification is intended to enhance social equity and ensure that affirmative action measures effectively target the most disadvantaged segments of society.",
